,Not Recommended,246620,16472678,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,[GPF] Bloodbag,"tldr:To be honest, the pricetag is the main reason I'm giving thumbs down. Otherwise, the game meets its own goal but I can't recommend it since it's painfully static and repetitive. I spent 2 hours playing it but it felt more like 20...Too long partThe game has very fascinating background and it's very exciting to discover everything it has to offer at first. But as you go on, you realise that while the content is wide, it's also quite shallow. You basically spend your time staring at a world map and some pulsing red dots progressively expanding over time.There are also red, orange and blue bubbles to pop every now and then, which in all honestly seems like a very very desperate attempt to make the gameplay look more dynamic. I imagine this whole concept works amazingly on mobile devices but it's just not good enough on a PC.Another way to spice things up is various events which occur in a more or less random fashion. Most of these are opportunities which can be abused to spread your disease faster. Problem is that these events tend to happen on the other side of the globe and you don't have enough resources to react in time.I also feel like there is a huge gap in the difficulty levels, asNormalcan basically be beaten by not actively doing anything at all whileBrutalseems almost impossible in comparison. If humanity starts working on a cure and you havent infected every single person on the planet yet, you basically lost the game because you usually don't have enough resources to deal with the cure development and security precautions. AtBrutalandMega Brutaldifficulties the discovery feels very random which is what makes it so hard and infuriating.Fun thing to note is that island countries become impenetrable fortresses once the cure development starts and you haven't infected anyone in there yet."
