,Recommended,246620,15325661,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,Cake Box Fox,"Fond memories of this as a browser game led me to believe that Madagascar would be the cause of my frustrations. This time it's Greenland that distrust everyone and close their port at the slightest whiff of any symptoms.The game is educational on both the infection spread and the geography of the world. And probably anger management.It's an early access game, but there is still plenty to do. I've not touched the scenarios yet, but the interaction with players on the design is a big plus.With the main game, it feels like the difficulty may be a barrier to some players and that locking content is a bit off putting when you lose your first normal game as you feel like you'll never be able to unlock anything whatsoever. Once you've got a rough strategy going (and playing games on casual unlocks helpful extras) of sneaky sneaky, kill 'em all before they can even think about starting a cure, you'll appreciate the subtle differences of the different plague types. Then will begin to find the game much more enjoyable and will start developing your own favourite techniques, such as, mega hordes of zombies invading the irritating surviving country, nasty symptom combos and mind control.The save function is useful as well, in case something doesn't go quite right or you just want to boot up a 100% infected world and wipe them out in whatever way you see fit. Whilst the world menus seemed useful, I didn't find myself using them much. Maybe they just need a little more polish. Who knows?pros--Lots of features-Steam workshop-Variety-Value for money-Quick to load-Easy to pick up and playCons-App style means it feels like it should be played on a touch screen.-Endless frustration at eagle-eyed researchers"
