76561198035271775,Recommended,246620,15882822,"Posted: 18 May, 2015",all,HeremitDevil,"In Plague Inc., you are literally a disease. Control your spreading, evolve your symptoms, evade the research for a cure and exterminate or subjugate the whole population on Earth through a world map interface.PROS+The mechanics are rather interesting: you are tasked with leading a plague to infect the whole world (and generally kill all mankind in some gruesome way), you choose your starting point and then use points to buy ""perks"" that adapt your plague to various biomes and situations (i.e. giving it more resilience to medications or allowing birds or else to spread it), develop various symptoms and resist to the inevitable research for a cure that will eventually start. It's cool, and well thought out.+There are multiple plagues that require different playstyles. Some are generic, some mutate on their own or travel slowly, others require being very fast in order not to accidentally kill all the infected before going worldwide, and so on. Necroa virus and the Planet of the Apes plague are particularly awesome and different from the standard plague, but Neurax Worm is also fun because of its double ending.+Achievement hunt is fun and satisfying, though it may require a guide to unlock some rather random events that lead to an achievement. Completing the plagues at the highest difficulty available is also a great challenge that increase the title's longevity for whoever likes its gameplay.+Workshop community is active enough and brings to the table many new interesting plague scenarios that further improve this game's appeal and variety.+Interface is simple but clean and enjoyable to look at.CONS-It can become rather repetitive after some time. After all, it's one mechanic, a brilliant one sure, but one only. Once you get used to infect the world and develop symptoms and other thingies, doing it again and again can get exhausting, also because a single playthrough may take quite some time to kick in. As said before, higher difficulty levels and custom scenarios by both developers and steam modders increase this game's longevity, but only to a certain extent for non-hyperfans.-At some moments, it can be rather boring to play, especially in earlier stages when you slowly start infecting some people and gain points veeeeeeeery slowly. Sometimes i just stared at the screen doing nothing for like 45 seconds, which may not seem much but when there's nothing interesting going on there it's quite some time.-Once the plague has been discovered and a cure research has started, mostly all the (expensive, point-speaking) things that a plague can do to defend itself are either lackluster (like barely reducing the research completion percentage) or seemingly completely worthless. It's rather frustrating when you invest some precious early points to ""slow down future research"", and then it still goes lightning-fast (like 1% per second, which is a lot, trust me) when it fully cranks up. Stealth playthroughs, in which you first infect the whole world then develop all the deadliest symptoms at once, are the more viable option, but they're also slow, boring and somewhat unrealistic (seriously, it doesn't matter if it has barely any symptoms, if something infects the whole world a cure should start ANYWAY).Plague Inc. is an atypical ""strategy"" game (it was born on cellphones, for the record) with simple but addicting mechanics and a good amount of gameplay variations, as much as its limited interface and its unique but one-dimensional playstyle allow. If you like what this game has to offer you'll play it for quite a while."
,Recommended,246620,16571149,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,hool10,"Remember that virus game you played a few years back? No? Well basically you create a virus and name it. You pick a country and mutate it based upon what country you placed it in. Say you mutate it so it transfers more easily via mosquito's in Chile rather than Russia and it goes crazy. Then you start devolping symptoms and in no time the world is taken over by your creation!The ""Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"" or CDC said that the game ""uses a non-traditional route to raise public awareness on epidemiology, disease transmission, and diseases/pandemic information. The game creates a compelling world that engages the public on serious public health topics"". They use also the models themselves to see what would happen as well and bigger red dots I think are based on real world populations. With China or Russia for example it goes crazy with infection.If your a zombie fan, history guy, or wondering ""what if I release the Bieber virus in Canada"" then this game is certainly worth it. Multiplayer is coming at the time of this review and I'm not sure how that would work. Best of all your helping that indie dev who made a great free app/flash game you loved and hated because you couldn't infect 1 guy in Madagascar. It's far more polished than that flash game."
