,Recommended,246620,9312233,"Posted: 1 March, 2014",all,Raizo,"Already in early access I'm absolutely enjoying this game.Since I've always liked games similar to this like Pandemic 1 & 2 it's hard for me not to love this game too.It has a simple mix of laid back strategy, chance and punny humor.The gameplay starts off by of popping little bubbles, as if it was on a phone, (it originally was), in hope to give you enough points to make some effects on your plague, varying from symptoms to transmissions and ""research complexity""... And then you wait (speed time up) and hope you don't get your plague detected before you've spread out at least a little, as your ultimate goal is to end humanity by killing everyone.Of course this comes with variations of diseases and parasites which changes the play style, each with their own advantages or disadvantages which may prove challenging.The addition of pretty graphics are alright, yet it does not enhance the gameplay.The music and atmosphere is sweet and generally just fits with the theme without being uncomfortable.Overall it's pretty solid, but could still use some improvements which seems to be worked on.I'll list a few things I did not like from the time I did this recommendation:Low variation of symptoms: Many diseases and parasites has the same ""symptom tree"" with the exception of the new Neurax Worm which is unique and absolutely brilliant. Amazing to play with, not so much the others as it is mainly too similar and dull.In-infectible countries: You may be playing the game, having infected the entire world with only one tiny island with closed borders and ports, yet it becomes completely impossible for you to infect the country with most plagues once this happens, immediately deciding that you won't be able to win. Even though, logically it would still be possible for the disease to be carried there, regardless of border control.Common geography: I've noticed a few countries have been fairly detailed in some areas but a bit too vague in other areas by calling them after the biggest country, then overlap the smaller neighboring countries, Yet it would have been more appropriate, for instance ""the balkan states"" which is absolutely correct, not too vague and not too detailed. While you see Germany overlap five different countries. Instead better naming would had been Southern Europe, Central Europe, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, Northern Europe, Scandinavia, Britain, Balkan States (even though technically still Eastern europe), etc.The pricing: Having to pay 30% more in Europe and only half price in Russia doesn't seem all that fair. If the pricing had a smaller percentage difference, maybe it would be more attractive globally.Still.. It's a fair game which I consider worth the money in contrast to its entertainment value."
