,Not Recommended,246620,30436433,Posted: 10 March,all,TheMetalOne,"-Assuming you're already familiar with this game-It's a good game, but you should just get it for your smart phone.It's the same game, minus some cosmetic stuff, and pre-set scenarios (mostly created by fans, NOT the dev...who has added nothing worthwhile to the PC release of this game). It's better to just get the same game, but be able to play it wherever you are.-For those NOT already familiar with either version of this game-In essence, this is a strategy game. Your goal is to infect, and kill, everyone in the world. You choose a type of disease (bacteria, virus, nano-virus, prion, fungus, etc.) and choose where you want the infection to start. Outside of the scenarios, each disease starts off the same way: no symptoms, easily controlled by various environments, and low infection rate. Each disease offers it's own unique benefit. As your disease slowly grows from a ""patient zero"" type thing, to something that more and more people have, you earn DNA points.These points are used to purchase upgrades for your disease; allowing you to indirectly control the effect the disease has on people, and how fast it spreads.The strategy piece of the game can be broken down into 3 catagories, different levels of which cause the world's population to take certain actions.1- Infection. If you upgrade your disease to be particularly infectious, it increases your chance of the world discovering the disease's existance. If your disease doesn't do much, it isn't much of an issue to get discovered. But...2- Severity. Increasing the symptoms of your disease can make it more infectious, causing it to spread quicker. The drawback is these symptoms almost always have some effect on how serious the disease gets taken. Something that only causes sneezing and a rash isn't going to cause too much of a fuss. However, once you start going for the more severe symptoms (such as ""Immune Suppression""), people are going to start trying to cure your disease.3- Lethality. The most severe symptoms can cause death, at varying rates. Once your disease starts killing people, the world will take notice. Borders, airlines, and ports can be closed to prevent further spreading. You will also have to race against the clock, as the world closes in on a cure. There are ways to delay, or reduce the progress of, the cure.There are also random world events that have an impact on the game. Too many to list here. A tutorial at the beginning of the game will go more in depth, but this is a good overview of what is going on in the game.Frankly, I've played the hell out of this game (mostly on my phone). I love it, and recommend it. Just don't bother with the PC version, unless you're one of the few people who don't own a smartphone. There's just no other reason to choose this version."
