76561198073830880,Recommended,246620,34854654,Posted: 9 September,all,oli.t678,A great casual strategy game that allows you to sit back and just see how everything unfolds. There is a good amount of replayability due to how many different types of plague there is you can choose from.
76561198054760998,Recommended,246620,9256145,"Posted: 25 February, 2014",all,Sherlock_Hemlock,"Plague Inc: Evolved is the port that cramped iPhone users have been waiting for, featuring all of the latest updates from the App version and has been well executed for the wider PC audience.Although it's obvious that little has changed between platforms, because even on the PC this game will boil down to 'Click the bubbles to get points --> spend points on upgrades --> win'. Hopefully in the ongoing steam updates this game will branch out into new areas more suited for PC gaming, which it is more than capable of doing. There is little going on here in terms of a plot, because of its iPhone roots but again we can hope this will be addressed.Having said all this, this game is incredibly addictive and although the £11.99 price tag is quite steep (as with most Early Access titles), you'll soon forget what was spent as you'll keep going until the game has been played, start to everything unlocked.Essentially, you play as some mystery overview character who can freely create diseases, whether they be based on bacteria, viruses, parasites, etc. etc. and you can freely infect 1 person anywhere on the planet, following that it's your job to evolve the disease by spending ""DNA Points"" to help infect more and more people across the globe until you've managed to wipe out the human race.Yes, you heard me right. It's not enough to infect everyone on the planet with some incurable nonsense like the common cold, but the game is truly won when you've evolved your pathogen of choice to have some pretty horrific symptoms and attempt to wipe out the entire human population.There are various difficulty levels but regardless of which you choose, trying to achieve your goal is a challenge. This game bills itself as a ""hyper realistic simulation"" of what would actually happen which means you have to think of and respond to various scenarios, these range from fairly obvious (some countries having better healthcare than others) to more complex (the Olympic Games means alot of people being gathered together in one place, ideal place to spread the disease). These little variants and the specific characteristics of the pathogens gives this seemingly simple platform alot of variation which will keep you coming back to finish it and check out the new updates.All in all, a good game, limited by the fact it's a mobile port, but will hopefully evolve into something more suited for PC gamers.6/10"
