,Recommended,246620,11224042,"Posted: 13 July, 2014",all,Joe respects women,"Overall, it was a pretty enjoyable game. Plesant graphics (never expected someone to say that about a strategy game, eh?), nice sound design and interesting game mechanics. Unique and sometimes downright hilarious update feeds ""Miners in Sweden find top notch mine"". It's just those little things that keep ya going.The Neurax Worm and the Necroa Virus were especially fun to play and offered a diverse gaming experience and broke up the monotony of common pathogen after common pathogen. I always find myself coming back to the worm. Am I being controled? The situations you can make with the Neurax Worm if you enslave humanity can range from awkward to hilarious ""Invader Zim enslaves humanity"". Like I said before, it's just those little things.The Necroa Virus, eh, I liked it. Nothing too spectacular, but still enjoyable. Difficult, yes. But it has this sort of satifaction when you beat it that most other plagues don't have. Except the worm, of course. It does, however, seem rather tedious trying to upgrade your zombie horde. Overall, it's my least favorite plague, but hey, in a game where all the Plagues are enjoyable, that isn't saying much. I especially like the Necroa music.The scenarios? I honestly have not played those yet.Ah, yes. the Simian Virus, I haven't seen the movie yet, but we're here to talk about the Simian Virus, no? The gameplay for the Simian Virus is challenging but not tedious.In the end, I give it 8 Bio-Weapons and a Virus out of 10 bio weapons (8.5 out of 10) The only things I can see improving upon are as follows : Updating the map (Crimea is no longer part of the Ukraine, petty, I know) and Making the upgrading of zombies less tedious. Other than that, it's a pretty good game in its present state. I'll update the review as the updates come rolling in"
