76561197980804400,Recommended,246620,9297980,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,Tantalus,"Initial Disclaimer:  I own both the mobile version (Plague Inc) and this version.  Most elements of this review apply to both versions.Summary:  Plague Inc: Evolved and its mobile counterpart are both great games - when they want to cooperate.  Plague Inc: Evolved has a cleaner, easier to use interface and a few extra features on Plague Inc, but they're essentially the same game.  If you have one, you're not missing out on anything groundbreaking by not having the other.  The biggest problems with the game are its randomness and lack of strategy.Details:  The game features a unique premise (wipe out all of humanity), functional graphics, and various addictive modes of play that keep me coming back time and time again.  Each plague you can use plays a little differently, though the basic strategy for success with all of them is basically the same.  My biggest complaint with the game is that later on, you get fewer and fewer bubbles to pop (other than cure bubbles), so if you didn't set yourself up properly from the very beginning, you are doomed to fail and all you can do is watch as you are eradicated.The game's random element makes choosing a difficulty setting almost moot.  This can make the game incredibly frustrating when you play on Casual and just want a quick, easy game.  Infecting everyone on the planet works pretty smoothly, but once you've done that, the influx of DNA points usually slows to a crawl - you no longer get red bubbles because everyone is already infected (which makes sense), but curiously, you also rarely get orange bubbles, and when you do, they're frequently worth much less than they used to be (usually only 1 pt).  At the same time, costs for all changes skyrocket, making those hyper-infrequent 1 pt orange bubbles essentially worthless when you still need 22 pts to buy the next symptom or ability.  This can very quickly leaves you in a situation where you can see that you're losing (humanity is creating a cure faster than you can kill them), but can't do a single thing about it.  On the other hand, you might be given a huge influx of points during play that means that you can easily afford all the symptoms you need later on in the game, which makes the game easy.  It kind of sucks feeling that your fate is completely beholden to some random number generator within the game's code.The game has multiple plague types, as I mentioned before, and they play a bit differently.  The virus, for example, mutates (develops symptoms) wildly.  On the other hand, the fungus doesn't spread across countries as quickly.  Despite the differences, there's really only one way to win - build up a couple abilities and transmissions while de-evolving any symptoms you get until you've infected everyone (making sure to stay undetected at the same time), then buy a whole bunch of lethal symptoms all at once.  If you're given enough DNA points through the course of the game to buy all the necessary lethal symptoms, you will win.  If you aren't, you will lose.  It's as simple as that."
